{
  "texts": [
    "3 See Ryan Calo & Danielle Keats Citron, The Automated Administrative State: A Crisis of Legitimacy, 70 EMORY L.J.",
    "797, 800-03 (2021) (discussing transparency, accountability, and due process concerns arising from the use of AI systems by federal and state agencies to automate decisionmaking); see also DAVID FREEMAN ENGSTROM, DANIEL E. HO, CATHERINE M. SHARKEY & MARIANO-FLORENTINO CUÉLLAR, ADMIN.",
    "U.S., GOVERNMENT BY ALGORITHM: ARTIFICIAL INTELLIGENCE IN FEDERAL ADMINISTRATIVE AGENCIES 7 (2020) (\"When public officials deny benefits or make decisions affecting the public's rights, the law generally requires them to explain why.",
    "Yet many of the more advanced AI tools are not, by their structure, fully explainable.",
    "A crucial question will be how to subject such tools to meaningful accountability and thus ensure their fidelity to legal norms of transparency, reason-giving, and non-discrimination.\")."
  ]
}